fields.title: Entrepreneur Lessons: When marketing outruns service delivery readiness
fields.description:
<ul>
<li>On our website we encourage our community members to give ratings after receiving products
fields.content:
• On our website we encourage our community members to give ratings after receiving products or services for the businesses on our platform.

 

It is encouraging to see that the reviews are largely positive. 

We celebrate those.

 

We have found that for those few where the feedback is not good, the root cause is oftentimes that the business owners get more business than they are ready for. 

 

This is a critical matter for us to look into as business owners.

The temptation is that we want as much business as possible. Sometimes, our marketing and sales are so good that we get more business than we can handle. 

 

In these times, we need to be able to be honest with our clients and tell them what we can deliver realistically.

We should avoid over-promising.

 

The positive experience of clients is a powerful marketing tool.

The negative experience of clients is a dangerous thing that causes reputational damage and loses trust in your business brand and in you as a person.

 

The lesson, ask for help and be honest if you cannot deliver on expectations.

 

It means much more because - building trust is critical for sustainable business success.

 

Sazi Ndwandwa CA (SA)

MPhil (Leadership Coaching)

 

About the Author

Sazi Ndwandwa is a business and leadership coach.

He is the CEO of GoldOurs (Pty) Ltd which helps companies and individuals to grow sustainably through three main service categories:

- Direction and strategy

- Talent management, leadership development, and training

- Systems and processes including internal audit, accounting & tax, and internal processes design & reviews.

fields.title: One hand can feed another”…a look at the phenomenon
Black Business Growth Initiative Calls for Unity, Heritage
fields.content:
Themed: “Black Business Growth Initiative Celebrating our Heritage, Carrying it into the Future, Building Legacies

 

The event takes place next Wednesday, (20 September 2023), at the Personal Trust House in Rondebosch, Cape Town. The BBGI reflects itself as a community of like-minded people united for the growth of Black African businesses and careers. The BBGI is going to discuss the importance of the female voice in black matters; the truths and myths around Women’s Day celebrations in South Africa; celebrating Black women with the support and buy-in of Black men.

 

Black Business Growth Initiative celebrates our beautiful and diverse heritage. We carry our heritage into our very bright future. 

 

“Through our individual heritage, we shall collectively build legacies for our nation.”

 

The BBGI asks several questions:

 

  • What aspects of your heritage do you want to take into the future to change the lives of your family and community?
  • What baton was handed over to you, that you want to pass on to the next generation?
  • Is your vision crystal clear and what tools do you have to chisel at this legacy every day?

 

Organisers are reaching out to the Black business community saying: “Come join Black Business Growth Initiative, as we sit around the proverbial fire and discuss our heritage with an esteemed panel of experts.”
